{"type":"message","id":"58dcdce0","parentId":"300936e7","timestamp":"2026-03-24T18:43:50.394Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0s71rtob1vfz_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 144318\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: the (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine the best action to advance the goals.\r\n\r\nCurrent situation:\r\n1. Phase 0 and Phase 1 architecture analysis are complete\r\n2. CFI Compression experiment was completed - found that:\r\n   - CFI ≥ 0.7 AND freq < 60 is TOO aggressive (loses 92.9% recall)\r\n   - Constant format tokens (freq=160, CFI=1.00) are metaprogramming artifacts\r\n   - Need THREE-DIMENSIONAL filter: CFI ≥ 0.5 AND freq ∈ [3, 120)\r\n3. Next pending experiment: Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring (Strategy C)\r\n   - Formula: score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120)\r\n\r\nThe most immediate next step according to the pending actions is the Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment. This is a concrete experiment that tests whether the new scoring formula can distinguish constant-format tokens from research trajectory tokens.\r\n\r\nI should run this experiment. Let me look at the existing CFI experiment files to understand the structure and then modify or create the experiment for Strategy C.\r\n\r\nLet me check what files exist related to the CFI experiment.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI Compression experiment revealed a critical insight: constant-format tokens (freq=160, CFI=1.00) are metaprogramming contamination, not true causal patterns. The next step is testing the hybrid scoring formula that should distinguish these from genuine research trajectory tokens.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nRun the Hybrid CFI×Freq scoring experiment (Strategy C) against the binary thresholds from the prior experiment, testing whether `score(T) = CFI(T) × min(1, freq(T)/120)` better handles constant-format tokens while